SIMPLE: gothic
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gothic
<hw>Goth"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>Gothicus</ets>: cf. F. <ets>gothique</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Pertaining to the Goths; <as>as, <ex>Gothic</ex>
customs</as>; also, rude; barbarous.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to a style of
architecture with pointed arches, steep roofs, windows large in
proportion to the wall spaces, and, generally, great height in
proportion to the other dimensions -- prevalent in Western Europe from
about 1200 to 1475 <sc>a. d.</sc> See <xex>Illust.</xex> of
<er>Abacus</er>, and <er>Capital</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gothic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Gothic
<hw>Goth"ic</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The language of the
Goths; especially, the language of that part of the Visigoths who
settled in Moesia in the 4th century. See <er>Goth</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Bishop Ulfilas or Walfila translated most of the Bible
into Gothic about the Middle of the 4th century. The portion of this
translaton which is preserved is the oldest known literary document in
any Teutonic language.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A kind of square-cut type, with no hair
lines.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <gothictype>This is Nonpareil GOTHIC.</gothictype>
</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>The style described in
<er>Gothic</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, 2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gothicism</ent>⟦br⟧
